<div id="review_3293730595" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3293730595" />
    <a title="Ciara Malaugh" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/57693571-ciara-malaugh"><img alt="Ciara Malaugh" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1583248253p2/57693571.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3293730595?book_show_action=true">May 04, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Ciara Malaugh" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Ciara Malaugh" href="/user/show/57693571-ciara-malaugh">Ciara Malaugh</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3293730595" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer9836850818304146061">A short but powerful novel about a love doomed before its inception by circumstance, Cal follows a young working-class boy in NI in the 80s. The country is only halfway through its 30-year-conflict that was the Troubles, and this seeps into every aspect of Cal’s life. He and his father are the only Catholic family left in their housing estate, and every time he walks home, he must be cognizant of his surroundings; boys from the neighborhood are ready to pounce on him and threaten his home with p</span>
  <span id="freeText9836850818304146061" style="display:none">A short but powerful novel about a love doomed before its inception by circumstance, Cal follows a young working-class boy in NI in the 80s. The country is only halfway through its 30-year-conflict that was the Troubles, and this seeps into every aspect of Cal’s life. He and his father are the only Catholic family left in their housing estate, and every time he walks home, he must be cognizant of his surroundings; boys from the neighborhood are ready to pounce on him and threaten his home with petrol bombs. The curb outside his house is adorned with red, white, and blue. It is clear they want his family out of the neighborhood. His friends are IRA vigilantes, dedicated to reuniting Ireland by any means necessary. Cal occasionally provides them with transportation, but overall, taking on a low-level war really isn’t his style. He simply wants to get a job where he doesn’t have to handle rotting animal carcasses, feel safe walking home, and sit at the library in his free time, admiring the beautiful Marcella.<br /><br />The prose is rather plain, yet it easily draws the reader into the story. I was invested in Cal’s well-being and eager to see the progress of his relationship with Marcella. I often found myself cringing or gasping as the story developed, and the author is quite adept at writing captivated dialogue. Indeed, I think the choice of prose was intentional— it was straightforward, sturdy, and bleak, embodying the mood of the Troubles. I was struck by how similar Cal’s story was to my father’s, so much so that I often called my dad to read aloud paragraphs that sounded like they were from one of his many stories from that era. If luck had gone a different way, my father’s fate could have been that of Cal’s. Thank god for teenage pregnancy, huh?</span>
  <a data-text-id="9836850818304146061" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


